I declare the 1st Drawing Contest opened


To take part in the Contest

Draw anything linked to the World of DinoRPG:

A dinoz you like or would like to see, a place, a landscape, a character, .....

Then scan it and upload on a picture hosting website like http://imageshack.us/

Just post your picture link in this topic to take part in the contest. Think about giving a title to your creation.

Rewards

The winners will be chosen by admins and mods

The rewards are:

* 1st - 150.000 coins
* 2nd - 100.000 coins
* 3rd - 50.000 coins
* 4th to 10th - 10.000 coins

Good luck and Enjoy

P.S.: Feel free to give your feedback / support for the creations you like.

Deadline: I will close this topic the 14th of June at midnight GMT + 1, so please submit your creation before

DinoSAR, my scanner does the same thing! What I usually do is fiddle with the brightness and contrast in Photoshop (Paint Shop Pro and similar programs also let you do that). Often, if you increase the contrast a little, and turn down the brightness, the color looks a lot more like it did on paper. You can also see if your program has a feature called "Levels." Photoshop's "Auto Levels" is a neat trick that works for many pictures.

[None]
As far as I understand it you are only allowed one entry, but doesn't necessarily have to be your first submission. I honestly don't recall them once saying all entries submitted after the first would be ignored, just that you can only select one of your pictures as an entry. Since you can add in proof that you drew the image (which includes line art, rough work and even other art work to prove you are able to draw) I'd say you just have to specify which is your chosen artwork.

What I know for sure is that you are allowed to submit a picture with just line art, or in black and white, and then later add a coloured in version. You are also allowed to fix errors that you've noticed in your drawings and make minor adjustments - from not adding your username to changing colours to adding an extra limb.

I would also assume that anyone who submitted before the deadline was set would be allowed to resubmit a new image regardless. On top of that, someone may wish to draw a better image after viewing some of the opposition's work to better their chances of winning - which is good for competition. But I would like to stress again that so far only non-mod/admins have said you may not change your entry, as far as I can see, but I could always be wrong.

Well, Enkidu there are a few problems there.

Firstly (and no offense to you Over2), I don't really trust Over's grammar and word choice to the ends of the Earth. Not because it's incorrect, but simply because he uses words that could be interpreted differently depending on the reader.

Secondly that doesn't actually go against anything I said. I mentioned the proofing and such and did say you're only allowed to submit one.

My sort of grey area comes in the submitting a new image. To me it's not clear that you can't change your mind on your one submission. I have seen I think 2 instances when someone did slight touch ups or editing and resubmitted which were accepted and added.
I think their reason for saying submit one, no multiple picture, etc. is so that people don't stand 2 chances of winning; kind of like buying 2 raffle tickets to double your chances.
Still, I'm quite sure if you asked nicely they would be glad to let you change your entry provided you give fair reason.

And in that respect people are making up rules. They take their interpretation of what the rules are and stick to it as though it was written on stone tablets.
Basically my point is that -due to the lack of definitive, unquestionable, lawyer-written rules- the rules may be bent slightly, should you be able to convince the mods/admins.
And the fact that we both have 2 completely different view points on the rules only stresses my point even further.
